		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Importance of a Speed Bump<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.39)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10537'>Eric "silverdrow" Splittgerber</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10537&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br>
THE IMPORTANCE OF A SPEED BUMP<br>
<br>
My friend Skyler Cuthill inspired this article.<br>
<br>
Here we are at the International Lord of the Rings Minion Speed-Bump Convention. We have had a great turnout so far from so many famous faces. Why look, theres Farin the Dwarf! And if Im not much mistaken that is the fabulous Haldir, accompanied by his usual party of Lorien Elves! This promises to be a most enjoyable day, and lets not forget that, later in the afternoon, we shall be having a special presentation from a very special person, who wishes to remain temporarily anonymous. I see so many wonderful people having a good time it almost makes me wish I were a strength four, vitality two companion just for the chance at some of these games. Over here we have an excitable group of Dwarf Guards playing a game of Name that Nazgul, and here, Thrarin and Gloin at Pin the Flame on the Balrog. They seem to be quite experienced at it. <br>
	Oh my, a group of Hobbits have just arrived, via ponies. Among them are many familiar faces, including Pippin: Mr. Took and Merry: From Oer the Brandywine. They seem to have brought their friend Bounder, along for the ride and the attractions no doubt. There is another, but I cant make his features out. WAIT! Could it be? IT IS! I could recognize that face anywhere! His talent has spread far and wide, his battle tactics a glory to behold. It is he, the one and only Sam: Proper Poet! It must be he, who is to give the speech later today.<br>
 I remember now, it was at the last tournament, they were at the Bridge of Kazad-Dum, The Balrog: Flame of Udin, coming out of the fiery depths of hell it seemed. And to all of our horror, the Witch-king: Lord of Angmar rode in too! All poor Gandalf and Aragorn could do was stand back among the Orcs, all too afraid to move. If only Boromir: Lord of Gondor were here, he and his Armor had never failed before, but alas, it was a bad draw this game. All looked hopeless and lost, when suddenly, out from behind the wallcrawlers and marksmen came a small cry. It was Sam; he looked so alone in this hostile realm, as if the whole world were against him. He came out, proud and fearless without a doubt or worry. He then proceeded to unleash such a daring display of tactics that it should shame even Elrond. He ran up to the Witch-king, did a barrel roll over his highness, and dove in-between the Balrogs legs, taking it by surprise. Losing its balance, it toppled, then, with a great cry, plummeted off the narrow stone bridge and down to the depths of Moria. And for the Witch-king, Sam undid his frying pan, and with a well places swing, knocked the Nazgul completely off his guard, he proceeded to administer smack after smack on the kneecaps, as they were the only things the hobbit could reach. He ended his attack with a spinning axe kick, that succeeded in knocking the Dark King down, beaten and humiliated, he stomped off with a bad limp in his better leg.<br>
 Thus the day was saved, and not by the brilliant force of Gondor Footmen, or an army of elves, but by a simple farmer, whos only wish was to cook for, and look after his master. See how useful a seemingly worthless companion can be?<br>
<br>
Ok, maybe you wont get to experience quite the thrill as was described in the passage above, but you should think of how important a well-chosen speed-bump can be. The official speed bump is something like a Dwarf Guard or a Lorien Elf, someone who cant do ANYTHING. Sure a dwarf player could buff up a Dwarf guard to strength twenty-seven and damage of somewhere between sixty and eighty-two. But wouldnt it be more useful to do the same to Gimli or Gloin? The point is that those companions were made for no reason other than being there to take on a Nazgul instead of your exhausted Aragorn. However, some other companions can be a speed bump in certain decks, in others, vital characters. The passage above was written in accordance to my deck Sauron N Speed bumps in which I use nine companions, six of which are there to die. My point is that I use Sam, Pippin, Merry, Gimli, and Gandalf as minion-stoppers. While someone elses deck may depend on Sam staying alive. <br>
One of the most important aspects of using a speed bump is knowing how to use it. What I mean is dont simply throw Pippin in front of a Morgul Warden if there is another way out. And I dont mean using Merry instead. You should strive to keep all your companions alive, yes even Pippin, for as long as you can use them. Hobbits are a great example of correctly using a speed bump; they have only three strength, but four vitality. That means they can be a useful archery sponge, a useful Isengard Orc, wounding sponge, and site exerting sponge. (E.G. Moria lake w/Frodo almost exhausted.) If you find yourself in a situation that gives you no choice, kill one of em off. Lets not go throwing away Boromir just to save a Lorien Elf. <br>
<br>
Another thing to look at is the capability to fight. I know hobbits are a wee bit on the weak side but couldnt there be ways to kill minions with them? One of the finest strategies is the Frying pan method. Simply attach one to your favorite hobbit and let er rip. Its oh so frustrating to see your opponents Merry take down an exhausted Morgul Hunter when they have eight companions. Believe me, I know. Merry From Oer the Brandywine is a very fine specimen indeed, a strength seven, vitality four companion can be useful especially Orc Swarms biggies like the Commander. Haldir is nice, after site six when he has strength of seven. Probably the worlds finest FIGHTING speed bump is Gandalf. That is if youre not playing a Gandalf deck. Since all of his cards have such nice game text its always worth a shot. I personally use The Grey Pilgrim, as I dont own FotSF and only my Sam has the Gandalf signet.  If you want to take a chance, add in Glamdring. Play a nice little twilight denial, and if you use it and only remove four, use it again.<br>
<br>
On a final note, I think everyone should have at least one well-chosen speed bump in his or her deck, as they have been known to save games. (come on, what has this whole article been about?) I am not going to list all the compatible ones out there, because everyone has a different opinion of what a speed bump should be. I will say this, if you select one, be sure it fits the following criteria:<br>
<br>
1) It has a reasonable vitality, a vit. One companion isnt worth the twilight used in most cases.<br>
2) He should be able to fight somehow, the exception is Sam, his purpose is his gametext, no matter which version youre playing. <br>
3) Make sure you really need him, and if hes there to die, no other purpose, dont put in any weapons or other cards regarding him, they will just take up deck space.<br>
<br>
Now, hopefully, you should be ready to decide if your deck requires a speed bump, good luck and god speed. , if you have any questions you can e-mail me at silverdrow20@hotmail.com, thank you for your time.<br>
<br>
Eric Splittgerber, part of the Rebel Strike Team<br>
